00:26:43,270 --> 00:26:46,300
not only looking at you, me old pal, but that pretty little wife of yours.

261
00:26:46,480 --> 00:26:48,840
Thought you were a spark, she did!

262
00:26:49,010 --> 00:26:53,910
And now your son's sinking into the selfsame bog that's swallowing you.

263
00:27:00,360 --> 00:27:01,850
See, Joey?

264
00:27:02,090 --> 00:27:03,990
l got the collar, too!

265
00:27:06,500 --> 00:27:08,260
Okay, come on, boy.

266
00:27:08,500 --> 00:27:10,400
Walk on. That's it.

267
00:27:12,500 --> 00:27:13,990
Walk on!

268
00:27:15,500 --> 00:27:16,990
Walk on, Joey.

269
00:27:18,240 --> 00:27:20,000
Come on, boy, walk on!

270
00:27:20,510 --> 00:27:24,880
You'd be better off standing at the top of the hill and going down!

271
00:27:25,980 --> 00:27:28,950
Gravity's the only friend you're gonna have today, young lad!

272
00:27:30,250 --> 00:27:32,410
Walk on, Joey! Walk on!

273
00:27:32,990 --> 00:27:34,890
Come on, Joey, walk on.

274
00:27:35,460 --> 00:27:37,150
Walk on, boy.

275
00:27:37,330 --> 00:27:39,950
Walk on. Come on, walk on.

276
00:27:42,930 --> 00:27:45,160
lt'll take the whip to move him.

277
00:28:12,290 --> 00:28:16,590
Bravo! You reached the top of the hill! Off you go again, boy!

278
00:28:17,030 --> 00:28:19,930
You'll make even better time coming down!

279
00:29:21,500 --> 00:29:24,260
That's the way. Now, come on, keep straight, boy. Good boy.

280
00:29:24,500 --> 00:29:28,270
Keep straight. Good lad. Good lad. Now walk on. Good boy.

281
00:29:28,500 --> 00:29:31,270
Good boy. Now come on, dig in!

282
00:29:33,040 --> 00:29:35,270
Albie, we're all with you!

283
00:29:35,510 --> 00:29:38,140
Come on, keep it straight, boy.

284
00:29:38,380 --> 00:29:41,010
That's it, walk on. Walk on.

285
00:29:41,180 --> 00:29:44,080
Look, look, the plow hasn't even cut yet.

286
00:29:49,990 --> 00:29:53,160
Do you know, l believe we can do it, Joey.

287
00:29:53,400 --> 00:29:56,090
l knew when l first saw you that you'd be the best of us.

288
00:29:57,000 --> 00:29:58,560
That's why he bought you.

289
00:29:59,130 --> 00:30:01,430
He knows you have all the courage he never had.

290
00:30:02,470 --> 00:30:05,370
l knew when l first saw you that you'd be the one who'd save us!

291
00:30:13,080 --> 00:30:14,450


292
00:30:16,550 --> 00:30:19,040
You've got no chance, lad.

293
00:30:19,290 --> 00:30:22,190
He'll not turn over half an acre. Give it up now.

294
00:30:22,360 --> 00:30:27,320
You've done well. You've tried hard. You're more of a man than your father.

295
00:30:27,700 --> 00:30:31,190
Come on now, Mr. Lyons, that's a bit rough, isn't it?

296
00:30:31,430 --> 00:30:33,730
Well, he'll destroy that horse.

297
00:30:41,180 --> 00:30:43,340
l'll be over Thursday.

298
00:30:44,180 --> 00:30:46,480
Give you a day to close it up.

299
00:30:53,660 --> 00:30:55,150
Your wool.

300
00:30:56,060 --> 00:30:57,620
l'm sorry, Rosie.

301
00:31:16,480 --> 00:31:17,780
Now, boy!

302
00:31:18,480 --> 00:31:20,240
You've got to do it, Joey!

303
00:31:20,480 --> 00:31:25,750
You don't know, so l'm going to have to do the knowing for you. The rest of our lives depend on this!

304
00:31:25,750 --> 00:31:30,250
So get set to pull! And pull straight! And pull hard!

305
00:31:33,230 --> 00:31:35,130
Now, boy! Go!

306
00:31:35,360 --> 00:31:38,390
Walk on, Joey, walk on! That's it!

307
00:31:38,630 --> 00:31:41,400
Good boy, Joey! Good boy!

308
00:31:48,380 --> 00:31:50,540
Walk on! Walk on!

309
00:31:50,780 --> 00:31:53,270
 Walk on! Walk on, Joey!

310
00:31:53,520 --> 00:31:57,820
Go on, walk on! That's it. Walk on. Walk on.

311
00:32:09,900 --> 00:32:11,390
Go around it!

312
00:32:11,730 --> 00:32:12,890
Whoa, Joey!

313
00:32:13,400 --> 00:32:15,700
Whoa, Joey! Joey!

314
00:32:16,540 --> 00:32:18,170
Joey! Whoa! Whoa!

315
00:32:18,410 --> 00:32:20,840
Joey, stop, you'll break the blade!

316
00:32:26,480 --> 00:32:28,710
Will you look at you!

317
00:32:30,690 --> 00:32:32,710
Mum, Dad! Come and look!

318
00:32:33,160 --> 00:32:34,450
He's doing it!

319
00:32:50,840 --> 00:32:52,740
Good lad, Albie!

320
00:32:55,580 --> 00:32:57,340
Albert, well done!

321
00:32:58,450 --> 00:33:00,470
l wouldn't have believed it!

322
00:33:00,650 --> 00:33:02,240
l'd not let a child of mine slip in the mud alongside a plow blade.

323
00:33:02,350 --> 00:33:05,590
He could lose a foot.

324
00:33:05,590 --> 00:33:10,730
You'll likelier lose an eye, Mr. Lyons, if you carry on prating at me how to manage my son!

325
00:33:10,730 --> 00:33:14,750
Or my plow, or my horse, or my field, or my farm!

326
00:33:22,200 --> 00:33:24,900
Come on, Albie! Push on through!

327
00:33:57,310 --> 00:34:00,610
Get it done, Albie! Get it done.

328
00:34:20,800 --> 00:34:23,700
Albie, are you all right?

329
00:34:23,930 --> 00:34:25,420
Are you all right?

330
00:34:28,800 --> 00:34:29,830
Up you get.

331
00:34:30,010 --> 00:34:33,300
My pair of fools. My mighty fools.

332
00:34:55,830 --> 00:34:58,320
You're as battered and bloodied as he is.

333
00:35:00,570 --> 00:35:02,870
Where's Dad? Still in the bottom field.

334
00:35:03,040 --> 00:35:04,530
Stumbling about, l suppose.

335
00:35:04,710 --> 00:35:07,470
lt's not the drink, Albert, that makes him stumble.

336
00:35:07,640 --> 00:35:10,870
He drinks, Mum! So might you if you'd been where he's been, seen what he's seen.

337
00:35:11,510 --> 00:35:12,810
He don't talk to me about it.

338
00:35:12,980 --> 00:35:16,680
He don't talk about it 'cause he can't. There aren't words for some things.

339
00:35:17,850 --> 00:35:18,880
Come here.

340
00:35:32,000 --> 00:35:33,900
The mice have been at it.

341
00:35:34,670 --> 00:35:35,970
Sit down.

342
00:35:42,540 --> 00:35:43,670


343
00:35:44,350 --> 00:35:46,040
lt's his campaign pennant.

344
00:35:46,480 --> 00:35:50,040
He were Sergeant, 7th Battalion, lmperial Yeomanry.

345
00:35:51,620 --> 00:35:55,320
And that is the Queen's South Africa Medal.

346
00:35:55,360 --> 00:35:58,380
Every man who fought in the Boer War got one of those.

347
00:35:58,890 --> 00:36:00,380
And this...

348
00:36:01,760 --> 00:36:03,920
That's the Distinguished Conduct Medal.

349
00:36:04,100 --> 00:36:07,470
Not Dad's? Well, it isn't mine, dear.

350
00:36:08,500 --> 00:36:10,940
He got that after the fighting at Transvaal.

351
00:36:11,110 --> 00:36:14,910
After he'd been hurt and he'd saved some other lads, and, well, l don't know what else.

352
00:36:14,910 --> 00:36:16,670
He won't tell me, either.

353
00:36:16,910 --> 00:36:19,070
But the first day he got home, he just tossed them out.

354
00:36:19,450 --> 00:36:24,520
First day he could walk, he threw them straight in the dustbin and wouldn't hear a word l said not to.

355
00:36:25,990 --> 00:36:29,890
See, what you done today, you and Joey, you're chuffed up now,

356
00:36:30,060 --> 00:36:33,430
and so you should be, my splendid boy.

357
00:36:33,660 --> 00:36:36,100
lt's good to be proud when you've done something good.

358
00:36:36,470 --> 00:36:40,770
But what he done in Africa, whatever it was, he takes no pride in it.

359
00:36:40,940 --> 00:36:44,630
Hard as it surely was and however much pain it's cost him,

360
00:36:45,410 --> 00:36:47,970
he refuses to be proud of killing, l suppose.

361
00:36:49,080 --> 00:36:50,840
l'd be proud.

362
00:36:51,410 --> 00:36:53,710
lf l'd gone off to war, if l'd gone and saved my mates...

363
00:36:53,880 --> 00:36:59,780
Whether or not you think you'd do the same thing as him, think how brave he is for refusing to be proud.

364
00:37:03,490 --> 00:37:08,030
Your dad makes mistakes, and he drinks to forget the mistakes that he's made,

365
00:37:09,100 --> 00:37:11,190
but he never gave up.

366
00:37:11,570 --> 00:37:13,730
And he does that for us.

367
00:37:14,700 --> 00:37:18,540
And today, you showed the world it's all been worth it.

368
00:37:19,710 --> 00:37:23,140
You keep looking after Joey, and he'll always be looking after you.

369
00:37:27,580 --> 00:37:30,750
''Sergeant, 7th Battalion, lmperial Yeomanry.''

370
00:37:33,460 --> 00:37:34,890
You see this, Joey?

371
00:37:35,720 --> 00:37:37,750
lt's been through an entire war.

372
00:37:42,800 --> 00:37:44,700
l'm not stealing it.

373
00:37:46,600 --> 00:37:48,690
l'll give it back to him someday.

374
00:38:32,050 --> 00:38:37,650
l'm the only boy that drives in the village. No one else drives but me. That's right, and this is my dad's car.

375
00:38:37,650 --> 00:38:43,050
You're lucky that you're in it。 l'm not normally allowed to drive it 'cause it's so...

376
00:38:45,790 --> 00:38:47,020
ls he a friend of yours?

377
00:39:03,680 --> 00:39:06,980
Come on, boy. Let's show her how to fly!

378
00:39:34,480 --> 00:39:38,070
Well, you're clearly not going to be a jumper.

379
00:40:04,140 --> 00:40:05,440
Shoo, Harold!

380
00:40:15,620 --> 00:40:17,640
We can try planting something else.

381
00:40:19,290 --> 00:40:21,590
Or we could hire ourselves out to Uncle Bob.

382
00:40:26,500 --> 00:40:29,120
How else are we gonna pay Mr. Lyons' rent?

383
00:40:44,380 --> 00:40:46,280
What are we going to do?

384
00:40:50,590 --> 00:40:52,610
l used to believe

385
00:40:53,460 --> 00:40:54,950
 that God

386
00:40:55,260 --> 00:40:58,280
gave each man his fair portion of bad luck.

387
00:40:59,930 --> 00:41:03,960
l don't feel that anymore. l've had more than my share.

388
00:41:06,540 --> 00:41:10,440
You'll stop loving me, Rose, and l won't blame you when you do.

389
00:41:13,070 --> 00:41:15,100
Well, l might hate you more,

390
00:41:15,940 --> 00:41:17,970
but l'll never love you less.

391
00:41:30,960 --> 00:41:32,520
lt's war!

392
00:41:32,960 --> 00:41:35,660
We are at war with Germany!

393
00:41:36,100 --> 00:41:41,130
You hear? England is at war with Germany!

394
00:41:43,510 --> 00:41:47,270
They're going to ring the bells at 6:00,

395
00:41:47,980 --> 00:41:52,280
and then never ring them again until the war is over.

396
00:42:00,390 --> 00:42:03,690
Look smart, Joey lad! lt's the Tavistock Fair!

397
00:42:18,070 --> 00:42:19,630
What has he done with him?

398
00:42:34,690 --> 00:42:37,590
First name, middle name, last. Sign.

399
00:42:38,030 --> 00:42:41,190
Last name first. First name, middle name, last.

400
00:42:41,700 --> 00:42:44,720
Take my word for it, finest horse in the parish.

401
00:42:45,100 --> 00:42:48,130
Goes like a racer, strong, decent, very fine.

402
00:42:48,370 --> 00:42:53,400
No curbs, no splints. Good feet and teeth. He's as sound as a bell, sir.

403
00:42:54,040 --> 00:42:55,600
And how much are you charging, sir,

404
00:42:56,040 --> 00:43:00,070
for this strong, decent, and very fine animal?

405
00:43:00,380 --> 00:43:01,610
Forty.

406
00:43:03,050 --> 00:43:05,350
l'll give you 20 and not a penny more.

407
00:43:05,590 --> 00:43:09,490
Twenty's no good to me, Captain. Thirtyfive and he's yours.

408
00:43:09,660 --> 00:43:11,820
l don't even know how he rides.

409
00:43:12,190 --> 00:43:15,090
Oh, he rides. Splendidly.

410
00:43:15,600 --> 00:43:18,090
You'll be astonished, l promise you that.

411
00:43:18,730 --> 00:43:20,830
Finest horse in all of Devon.

412
00:43:22,070 --> 00:43:24,230
Finest horse l've ever seen.

413
00:43:30,680 --> 00:43:32,170
Thank you.

414
00:43:40,620 --> 00:43:42,110
You can't.

415
00:43:43,220 --> 00:43:45,250
You can't. He's mine.

416
00:43:45,430 --> 00:43:47,190
l trained him. Albert.

417
00:43:47,360 --> 00:43:48,850
You can't have him. He's my horse, sir.

418
00:43:49,230 --> 00:43:52,200
l'm afraid it's too late, lad. l've just paid 30 guineas for him.

419
00:43:52,630 --> 00:43:55,260
Please. l'll get you money.

420
00:43:56,640 --> 00:44:00,270
l will, l'll get you money. l'll work for it.

421
00:44:00,780 --> 00:44:02,270
l'll work for it.

422
00:44:07,120 --> 00:44:08,810
He won't obey anyone else.

423
00:44:09,580 --> 00:44:12,820
He won't be any good in the war neither. He shies at every sound.

424
00:44:14,390 --> 00:44:15,690
l'm sorry.

425
00:44:17,390 --> 00:44:19,830
Well, if Joey's going, l'm going, too. l'm volunteering.

426
00:44:20,660 --> 00:44:22,820
l see. What's your name, lad? Albert, sir.

427
00:44:23,200 --> 00:44:24,760
And how old are you, Albert? Nineteen, sir.

428
00:44:25,830 --> 00:44:26,990
ls that the truth?

429
00:44:27,300 --> 00:44:29,330
 No, sir, but l look 1 9

430
00:44:29,370 --> 00:44:32,670
and l'm bigger than most 1 9yearolds, and l'm strong, sir, and l'm not afraid of anything.

431
00:44:32,670 --> 00:44:38,810
l don't doubt your qualifications, Albert, but the law is very clear about the proper age for soldiering.

432
00:44:38,810 --> 00:44:41,650
Your father's done what he had to do, you know that.

433
00:44:43,420 --> 00:44:47,320
Thirty guineas isn't nearly enough to purchase a horse

434
00:44:47,490 --> 00:44:49,250
as fine as your Joey, l know that.

435
00:44:49,420 --> 00:44:51,190
But it's all l've got.

436
00:44:52,290 --> 00:44:56,320
Will you lease him to me, Albert? To be my own mount?

437
00:44:59,830 --> 00:45:05,570
l promise you, man to man, that l'll look after him as closely as you've done.

438
00:45:05,570 --> 00:45:09,740
l'll respect him and all the care that you've taken with him.

439
00:45:10,580 --> 00:45:14,610
And if l can, l'll return him to your care.

440
00:45:21,320 --> 00:45:22,620
Now say goodbye.

441
00:45:26,530 --> 00:45:27,550
lt's all right.

442
00:45:27,660 --> 00:45:31,620
All right, turn it in. That's enough. He's a horse, not a dog.

443
00:45:31,800 --> 00:45:34,230
Now on your way. Come on!

444
00:45:40,740 --> 00:45:43,910
Do you want to lose the farm? Rose?

445
00:45:46,210 --> 00:45:47,910
lt's the way you did it.

446
00:45:50,350 --> 00:45:52,250
But we're at war.

447
00:45:54,490 --> 00:45:56,250
Aren't we just?

448
00:46:32,260 --> 00:46:33,280
Joey.

449
00:46:33,460 --> 00:46:34,830
l told you, sling your hook!

450
00:46:35,000 --> 00:46:37,020
Let him be, Perkins.

451
00:46:38,930 --> 00:46:41,830
This isn't the end. This isn't the end, my brother.

452
00:46:42,000 --> 00:46:45,560
l, Albert Narracott, solemnly swear we will be together again.

453
00:46:45,740 --> 00:46:49,970
Wherever you are, l will find you, and l will bring you home.

454
00:47:07,830 --> 00:47:10,590
Steady, steady. Steady now, come on!

455
00:47:10,830 --> 00:47:14,730
Walk on! Walk on, come on! Get on!

456
00:47:29,850 --> 00:47:32,750
Take good care of him. Yes, sir. l will.

457
00:47:56,340 --> 00:47:58,510
Whoa, whoa, whoa! Easy. Easy.

458
00:48:01,480 --> 00:48:02,640
Easy.

459
00:48:14,030 --> 00:48:17,400
Steady, steady. Whoa, whoa, Joey!

460
00:48:17,630 --> 00:48:21,400
Stop mucking about, you hear? You're in the army now, son.

461
00:48:21,900 --> 00:48:24,930
Good boy. Good boy. Steady.

462
00:48:25,770 --> 00:48:28,670
Steady, steady. Come on. Easy, come on.

463
00:48:28,910 --> 00:48:31,070
Come on, around. Good boy.

464
00:48:32,510 --> 00:48:33,810
Relax.

465
00:48:35,050 --> 00:48:36,950
Easy, easy, back up!

466
00:48:39,520 --> 00:48:41,420
Joey, meet Topthorn.

467
00:48:41,660 --> 00:48:43,420
Topthorn, this is Joey.

468
00:48:43,590 --> 00:48:46,420
Sort out who's in charge between the two of you. Do you hear?

469
00:48:46,590 --> 00:48:48,760
lf you want to fight, get it over with 'cause once we're over there,

470
00:48:48,930 --> 00:48:52,660
you're going to need everything you've got for Fritz.

471
00:48:52,730 --> 00:48:56,430
Gently, Perkins. l don't want to sour him.

472
00:48:56,600 --> 00:49:01,140
There'll be nothing gentle about the war, sir. And there'll be nothing gentle about this one, either.

473
00:49:01,140 --> 00:49:04,170
l understand that, Sergeant, but l want him fit and shining.

474
00:49:04,750 --> 00:49:06,040
He's my horse.

475
00:49:06,410 --> 00:49:07,440
Sir.

476
00:49:08,950 --> 00:49:10,440
Easy, boy.

477
00:49:11,690 --> 00:49:13,920
Scares the living daylights out of me.

478
00:49:14,090 --> 00:49:17,720
Who? Perkins. Glad he's on our side.

479
00:49:17,960 --> 00:49:20,720
Not bad. Not bad at all.

480
00:49:21,700 --> 00:49:24,860
Still, not a patch on my Topthorn.

481
00:49:25,500 --> 00:49:28,200
l wouldn't be so sure. l think he's got potential.

482
00:49:28,770 --> 00:49:31,530
He's certainly got the bit between his teeth.

483
00:49:31,710 --> 00:49:34,730
l actually think my Blenheim's faster than the pair of them.

484
00:49:35,440 --> 00:49:36,740
Clear off.

485
00:49:40,580 --> 00:49:42,140
All right, gentlemen, listen here.

486
00:49:42,780 --> 00:49:45,880
Everything tells us the same story, from Waterloo to Omdurman,

487
00:49:46,050 --> 00:49:48,550
from Pickett's Charge to the Battle of MarslaTour.

488
00:49:48,720 --> 00:49:52,160
The first attack can and should be the decisive one. Perkins?

489
00:49:52,530 --> 00:49:56,000
Yes, sir. No excuses, no mistakes. Every horse groomed and fit for presentation.

490
00:49:56,000 --> 00:49:58,630
l want a full practice charge tomorrow. Sir.

491
00:50:07,940 --> 00:50:09,640
l thought you two had bottled out.

492
00:50:09,780 --> 00:50:11,070
As if.

493
00:50:14,850 --> 00:50:17,680
All right, then. Let's see what you two jokers are made of, shall we?

494
00:50:17,850 --> 00:50:19,680
This is what quiet confidence looks like.

495
00:50:19,850 --> 00:50:21,620
l'll wait for you two at the Duke of York.

496
00:50:24,130 --> 00:50:25,890
Over to you, Captain Nicholls.

497
00:50:29,800 --> 00:50:32,100
Draw swords!

498
00:50:34,670 --> 00:50:36,570
Give point!

499
00:50:38,940 --> 00:50:40,700
Charge!

500
00:50:59,090 --> 00:51:03,590
Come on, Joey, l know you've got it. Come on, boy!

501
00:51:18,580 --> 00:51:19,740
Come on, boy!

502
00:51:38,270 --> 00:51:39,760
Nice of you to turn up.

503
00:51:39,930 --> 00:51:43,030
He's got speed, l'll give him that. But has he got stamina?

504
00:51:43,270 --> 00:51:45,030
He has everything.

505
00:52:03,160 --> 00:52:04,650
What are you up to?

506
00:52:05,030 --> 00:52:06,650
l'm writing a letter.

507
00:52:07,160 --> 00:52:08,920
With a picture in it?

508
00:52:10,900 --> 00:52:16,170
lt's to the boy who owned Joey. l want to show him how wonderful he's looking.

509
00:52:16,170 --> 00:52:19,800
Before we take him across the Channel to face a million German guns.

510
00:52:19,970 --> 00:52:21,270
Yes, before that.

511
00:52:22,380 --> 00:52:26,650
4:00 a.m. start tomorrow, traveling with the Dragoon Guards and the Royals. Transport detachment.

512
00:52:26,650 --> 00:52:29,780
They need to be at the dock at 5:00 a.m. to check all the kit.

513
00:52:29,780 --> 00:52:31,950
Battle orders, no polishing.

514
00:52:32,120 --> 00:52:36,150
Buttons, helmet buckles, stirrup irons, let them all go dull.

515
00:52:36,320 --> 00:52:39,830
l don't want anything to flash in the sun and give us away. Of course.

516
00:52:40,800 --> 00:52:42,350
Charlie. Jamie.

517
00:52:43,200 --> 00:52:44,360
Charlie.

518
00:52:48,940 --> 00:52:50,700
What do you think of the new cap?

519
00:52:54,140 --> 00:52:56,910
Silk lining. l quite like it.

520
00:52:57,210 --> 00:52:59,840
l'm not sure it's going to make a lot of difference to the Germans.

521
00:53:00,010 --> 00:53:02,450
Oh, l don't know about that. Think about it.

522
00:53:02,820 --> 00:53:06,120
You're a Boche, just working out which of two chaps to shoot,

523
00:53:06,290 --> 00:53:11,090
and you thought, ''Good Lord, ''one of them really is wearing a very stylish cap indeed!''

524
00:53:11,090 --> 00:53:12,460
You might shoot the other one instead.

525
00:53:13,360 --> 00:53:18,390
Or alternatively think, ''l fancy that cap,'' and kill you first of all.

526
00:53:22,370 --> 00:53:23,390
Hadn't thought of that.

527
00:53:33,980 --> 00:53:37,880


528
00:53:53,000 --> 00:53:55,605
That is our target,the German 11 th Division, at the moment bivouacked three miles to the east of the Menin Road.

530
00:53:58,210 --> 00:54:02,080
We have been watching them, and they have pitched tents for the night and lit cooking fires.

531
00:54:02,080 --> 00:54:07,010
Knock them out and we could slide in behind the German lines and come at them from the south at Geluveld.

532
00:54:07,010 --> 00:54:08,040
Excellent.

533
00:54:08,220 --> 00:54:10,450
Numbers? About 600, infantry.

534
00:54:10,890 --> 00:54:13,950
Twice our size. Regiments of horse and men, the advantage is ours.

535
00:54:13,950 --> 00:54:16,620
And we have surprise on our side. But the sooner we move, the better.

536
00:54:16,660 --> 00:54:18,820
We have no assurance they'll still be there tomorrow morning.

537
00:54:19,030 --> 00:54:23,500
Right. Good. So today it is. Charlie, tell the men.

538
00:54:23,500 --> 00:54:27,500
Salisbury formation? Salisbury formation. Charge through them and secure the ground behind.

539
00:54:27,500 --> 00:54:30,200
The grass to the left is taller than we are, it's perfect cover.

540
00:54:30,370 --> 00:54:34,310
Excellent work, Sergeant Major. Time spent on reconnaissance is rarely wasted.

541
00:54:34,310 --> 00:54:35,800
Thank you, Singh.

542
00:54:36,440 --> 00:54:37,810
Jamie!

543
00:54:39,980 --> 00:54:41,540
They have no idea we're coming.

544
00:54:41,920 --> 00:54:44,080
Not having scruples, are you, Jim?

545
00:54:44,790 --> 00:54:47,950
No, l understand the surprise is everything.

546
00:54:49,320 --> 00:54:51,810
But if it must be done, let's do it quickly.

547
00:54:58,030 --> 00:54:59,330
You all right, Charlie?

548
00:55:01,940 --> 00:55:03,230
Never been better.

549
00:55:03,940 --> 00:55:06,500
Literally. Never better.

550
00:55:09,810 --> 00:55:12,510
Prepare to mount! Mount!

551
00:55:14,350 --> 00:55:16,110
Prepare to mount!

552
00:55:16,820 --> 00:55:17,840
Mount!

553
00:55:18,090 --> 00:55:19,520
Thank you, Stanley.

554
00:55:23,360 --> 00:55:24,920
Hey, Joey.

555
00:55:25,960 --> 00:55:27,390
My bonny boy.

556
00:55:33,570 --> 00:55:35,590
You're all right, aren't you, Joey?

557
00:56:03,430 --> 00:56:07,420
Gentlemen, it is an honor to ride beside you.

558
00:56:08,400 --> 00:56:12,430
Make the Kaiser rue the day he dared to cross swords with us.

559
00:56:13,540 --> 00:56:17,910
Let every man make himself, his King, his country,

560
00:56:18,150 --> 00:56:20,580
and his fallen comrades proud.

561
00:56:22,020 --> 00:56:23,310
Be brave.

562
00:56:24,150 --> 00:56:27,050
Fear God! Honor the King!

563
00:56:27,290 --> 00:56:29,920
Fear God! Honor the King!

564
00:56:45,170 --> 00:56:47,940
Draw swords!

565
00:56:50,040 --> 00:56:51,340
Good luck, my friends.

566
00:56:58,320 --> 00:56:59,950
Forward, to walk!

567
00:57:00,920 --> 00:57:03,480
Walk, march!

568
00:57:12,200 --> 00:57:14,220
Forward, to canter!

569
00:57:17,070 --> 00:57:19,970
Canter, march!

571
00:57:57,510 --> 00:57:59,270
Charge!

572
00:58:40,090 --> 00:58:41,380
Burn the documents!

573
01:00:13,510 --> 01:00:15,540
Pull him down!

574
01:00:36,540 --> 01:00:41,570
What? Did you think that a garrison on open ground would go undefended?

575
01:00:42,410 --> 01:00:44,170
Look at yourself!

576
01:00:45,410 --> 01:00:47,440
Who do you think you are?

577
01:01:47,610 --> 01:01:48,910
Now come!

578
01:02:06,760 --> 01:02:09,790
What do we do with the horses? lf they're injured, shoot them.

579
01:02:09,960 --> 01:02:13,720
And the others, sir? The others you round up and take to base camp. They will pull guns.

580
01:02:13,770 --> 01:02:17,260
You'll never get fancy horses like these to pull guns.Then shoot them also! 

581
01:02:17,440 --> 01:02:23,070
Sir? Perhaps we could use some of them with the ambulances, to get the injured men off the field.

582
01:02:24,510 --> 01:02:26,950
Will they take the harness? l'd like to try, sir.

583
01:02:32,190 --> 01:02:33,810
lt won't work. They're cavalry.

584
01:02:34,090 --> 01:02:35,650
Let's try. You won't get the harness on.

585
01:02:35,760 --> 01:02:37,120
Come on, Michael.

586
01:02:39,160 --> 01:02:42,650
Easy now. Easy now, Englishman. Easy.

587
01:02:45,500 --> 01:02:48,260
Easy. Easy. Easy.

588
01:02:48,500 --> 01:02:49,590
Easy now.

589
01:02:50,700 --> 01:02:51,800
Gunther.

590
01:02:53,110 --> 01:02:55,440
lt's hopeless. We can't help them.

591
01:03:20,570 --> 01:03:22,660
Well, well, look at you.

592
01:03:23,470 --> 01:03:26,300
Whoever taught you this has just saved your life.

593
01:04:08,780 --> 01:04:10,550
Hello, the farm!

594
01:04:11,450 --> 01:04:12,680
Hello, Si Easton.

595
01:04:13,450 --> 01:04:15,420
l was at the post office.

596
01:04:15,590 --> 01:04:20,290
And while l was there, Mrs. Allen said a parcel had come for Albert from the...

597
01:04:21,530 --> 01:04:22,690
From the...

598
01:04:23,730 --> 01:04:25,360
From over there. And l thought

599
01:04:25,530 --> 01:04:28,630
l could go up that way in the morning, and here it is.

600
01:04:30,600 --> 01:04:32,770
Who'd be sending me a parcel over there?

601
01:04:32,940 --> 01:04:34,840
Well, open it and see.

602
01:04:46,690 --> 01:04:48,450
lt's a sketchbook.

603
01:04:51,290 --> 01:04:53,260
lt's Captain Nicholls' sketchbook!

604
01:04:53,690 --> 01:04:55,660
See that? That's a picture of Joey!

605
01:04:55,830 --> 01:04:57,730
lt's a picture of Joey.

606
01:04:58,370 --> 01:04:59,660
Well, l never!

607
01:04:59,830 --> 01:05:01,390
And there's a letter.

608
01:05:01,970 --> 01:05:03,730
Well, go on then, go on.

609
01:05:04,640 --> 01:05:08,270
''Dear Albert Narracott, Captain Nicholls, who died...

610
01:05:09,680 --> 01:05:13,740
''Captain Nicholls, who died in action today, left you this. ''Yours, Sergeant Sam Perkins.''

611
01:05:14,380 --> 01:05:16,410
You weren't to know it was bad news.

612
01:05:16,580 --> 01:05:18,610
He was riding Joey when he died.

613
01:05:18,790 --> 01:05:22,280
You don't know that he was riding him. ''ln action,'' it says.

614
01:06:16,080 --> 01:06:17,570
Gentlemen!

615
01:06:19,580 --> 01:06:22,880
We move forward to the front line tonight.

616
01:06:23,920 --> 01:06:26,550
Full marching orders.

617
01:06:27,590 --> 01:06:29,020
Get moving!

618
01:06:29,860 --> 01:06:31,350
Schroeder!

619
01:06:31,530 --> 01:06:34,360
No, not you. You. Come.

620
01:06:35,530 --> 01:06:39,930
l'm keeping you here. You're best with the horses, and we need to move the camp quickly

621
01:06:39,930 --> 01:06:42,490
if the enemy continues to push through from the west.

622
01:06:42,670 --> 01:06:44,830
They're pushing through? l'm told.

623
01:06:45,010 --> 01:06:47,910
We will move later, when we find where the horses are needed most.

624
01:06:48,110 --> 01:06:52,780
Yes, sir. Perhaps l can keep my brother here with me. He's also very good with horses.

625
01:06:52,780 --> 01:06:55,610
No. Not necessary. Get moving, we leave tonight.

626
01:07:03,960 --> 01:07:05,720
lt's all right, Gunther.

627
01:07:10,630 --> 01:07:12,530
You are not going.

628
01:07:12,700 --> 01:07:16,000
l'll tell them you're only 1 4. That you're a boy.

629
01:07:16,470 --> 01:07:19,770
Father signed me in. He knew my age. And so do they.

630
01:07:23,980 --> 01:07:26,340
Mother obviously never told you how to fold a shirt.

631
01:07:26,480 --> 01:07:28,240
Of course she did. l just wasn't listening.

632
01:07:28,480 --> 01:07:31,110
But you need to listen now. l promised her.

633
01:07:31,790 --> 01:07:35,690
l made her a solemn promise that you would be safe with me.

634
01:07:35,920 --> 01:07:37,690
With me, Michael.

635
01:07:42,060 --> 01:07:47,070
They'll never make a head count. There are too many of us. You can stay here.

636
01:07:47,070 --> 01:07:49,430
Slip underneath the bed, until they move out.

637
01:07:49,670 --> 01:07:50,970
Then what?

638
01:07:53,410 --> 01:07:55,770
Gunther, it will be fine.

639
01:07:56,480 --> 01:08:00,570
And when all the machines break down and they call up the horses,

640
01:08:01,750 --> 01:08:03,650
l'll see you at the front.

641
01:08:04,680 --> 01:08:06,520
We'll be together again.

642
01:08:08,960 --> 01:08:10,050
Gunther.

643
01:08:26,510 --> 01:08:28,800
l'm giving this to you. For luck.

644
01:08:37,650 --> 01:08:39,080
To keep you safe.

645
01:09:57,260 --> 01:09:59,760
Get back in line!

646
01:10:31,770 --> 01:10:34,130
l'm hungry. Did you bring food?

647
01:10:34,300 --> 01:10:35,790
l'm sorry.

648
01:10:41,010 --> 01:10:44,640
Will Father be ashamed? He will pretend to be.

649
01:10:45,310 --> 01:10:47,340
Maybe at first he will be.

650
01:10:50,080 --> 01:10:51,980
But in the end, he will be glad.

651
01:10:53,320 --> 01:10:54,810
And us?

652
01:10:56,060 --> 01:10:57,680
What about us?

653
01:11:05,930 --> 01:11:07,960
l was ready to go.

654
01:11:10,800 --> 01:11:12,830
l was proud to go.

655
01:11:15,710 --> 01:11:17,400
l wanted to go.

656
01:11:27,690 --> 01:11:29,710
The food in ltaly is good.

657
01:11:30,020 --> 01:11:31,050
Yes.

658
01:11:33,230 --> 01:11:35,160
And what about the women?

659
01:11:36,830 --> 01:11:38,730
Not as good as the food.

660
01:11:39,170 --> 01:11:40,390
Because 

661
01:11:41,900 --> 01:11:43,930
they've eaten too much of the food?

662
01:11:45,110 --> 01:11:48,730
You are too young for war and you're too young for women!

663
01:11:48,910 --> 01:11:50,670
l don't feel so young.

664
01:11:53,250 --> 01:11:55,210
Not anymore. Michael.

665
01:11:55,650 --> 01:11:57,740
What? Go to sleep.

666
01:11:57,980 --> 01:11:59,950
We have a big night of riding ahead.

667
01:12:02,390 --> 01:12:04,020
Good night, Michael.

668
01:12:10,130 --> 01:12:11,760
Nightnight, Gunther.

669
01:13:11,260 --> 01:13:13,350
Schroeder. Yes, sir.

670
01:13:14,790 --> 01:13:16,160
A mistake?

671
01:13:20,000 --> 01:13:21,300
A promise.

672
01:15:08,910 --> 01:15:10,340
lt's closer today.

673
01:15:10,510 --> 01:15:14,280
The wind plays tricks with the noise. lt's moving away from us.

674
01:15:14,510 --> 01:15:16,540
l can hear it, grandpere.

675
01:15:16,920 --> 01:15:18,540
And there is no wind.

676
01:15:19,250 --> 01:15:21,080
You shouldn't lie to me.

677
01:15:21,250 --> 01:15:23,480
Here. There is no wind here.

678
01:15:23,860 --> 01:15:28,880
But over there, the wind is so strong it will lift you off the ground.

679
01:15:30,200 --> 01:15:33,220
You lie about everything!

680
01:15:34,430 --> 01:15:37,670
You say you aren't worried, but it's clear you are.

681
01:15:38,200 --> 01:15:40,100
l know the war is approaching,

682
01:15:40,270 --> 01:15:43,640
but you say, ''Oh, it's just a trick of the wind.''

683
01:15:44,040 --> 01:15:45,410
Did l say that?

684
01:15:45,610 --> 01:15:48,380
You started lying when Mama and Papa went away.

685
01:15:51,220 --> 01:15:52,510
They're dead.

686
01:15:53,090 --> 01:15:54,640
But you won't say so.

687
01:15:55,150 --> 01:15:57,180
Do you think l'll die if you tell me the truth?

688
01:15:57,360 --> 01:15:59,120
The truth is

689
01:16:00,430 --> 01:16:04,060
you should speak to your elders with respect.

690
01:16:12,010 --> 01:16:14,440
lf you tell me the truth about the war,

691
01:16:14,970 --> 01:16:19,000
l will tell you the truth about the big horses

692
01:16:19,450 --> 01:16:21,610
l've been keeping in the windmill.

693
01:16:22,920 --> 01:16:26,210
Now who is the one telling lies?

694
01:16:27,450 --> 01:16:29,080
ln the windmill?

695
01:16:29,260 --> 01:16:33,420
Yes. They were standing in the windmill waiting for Don Quixote.

696
01:16:34,260 --> 01:16:37,020
This is Francois and this is Claude.

697
01:16:37,460 --> 01:16:40,360
l named them after two boys who broke my heart last summer.

698
01:16:40,530 --> 01:16:42,430
They must belong to someone.

699
01:16:42,570 --> 01:16:45,540
Horses like this don't just appear from a fairy tale.

700
01:16:45,670 --> 01:16:48,570
Yes, l know, grandpere. They are not unicorns.

701
01:16:49,010 --> 01:16:51,170
So l will be fair and wait one day,

702
01:16:51,410 --> 01:16:52,710


703
01:16:53,010 --> 01:16:55,310
and if no one comes to get them by nighttime,

704
01:16:55,620 --> 01:16:58,180
then they belong to me.

705
01:16:58,350 --> 01:17:00,510
Emilie, look at me.

706
01:17:02,960 --> 01:17:04,390
You cannot ride.

707
01:17:04,560 --> 01:17:06,930
Mother used to tell me how my bones would give way with the slightest bump or fall.

708
01:17:06,930 --> 01:17:11,520
Yes. That's right. So, it is settled?

709
01:17:13,570 --> 01:17:14,730
Good girl.

710
01:17:16,570 --> 01:17:21,200
lt will only be settled when l decide which one to ride first.

711
01:17:23,040 --> 01:17:25,010
Over my dead body!

712
01:17:25,180 --> 01:17:27,200
At least l won't have long to wait!

713
01:17:47,600 --> 01:17:51,090
l was in love with a boy called Francois, who had your lovely eyes.

714
01:17:51,270 --> 01:17:55,570
Unfortunately, he was in love with a girl called Marie, who had your teeth.

715
01:17:55,740 --> 01:17:58,640
She fell for a boy called Claude, who broke my heart

716
01:17:59,010 --> 01:18:00,950
and who l intend to marry one day.

717
01:18:06,020 --> 01:18:07,320
Eyes on me.

718
01:18:08,420 --> 01:18:09,720
No talking.

719
01:18:10,420 --> 01:18:12,790
Today, we learn to jump.

720
01:18:13,290 --> 01:18:17,700
Did you know the French cleared the 1 .85 meter at the Paris Olympics

721
01:18:17,730 --> 01:18:21,220
to win the gold medal? Today, we will beat that record.

722
01:18:24,300 --> 01:18:25,740
This is your jump.

723
01:18:26,110 --> 01:18:29,270
When l call you, be very brave and leap over it!

724
01:18:31,380 --> 01:18:33,140
Leap over it!

725
01:18:33,310 --> 01:18:34,400
Watch me.

726
01:18:38,790 --> 01:18:40,750
And now it's your...

727
01:19:20,430 --> 01:19:24,800
He doesn't think we can do it. But we will show him, won't we?

728
01:19:38,710 --> 01:19:40,740
No need to be afraid.

729
01:19:43,250 --> 01:19:46,150
You are very tall.

730
01:19:48,650 --> 01:19:50,680
You'll kill yourself.

731
01:19:50,860 --> 01:19:52,880
Only if you get in my way to make me fall.

732
01:19:53,260 --> 01:19:55,560
Oh, please. Come off the...

733
01:20:07,470 --> 01:20:09,500
Find somewhere to hide them.

734
01:20:09,740 --> 01:20:11,510
And do it quickly.

735
01:20:48,780 --> 01:20:53,220
My name is Bonnard. This is my land. Why are you here?

736
01:20:53,390 --> 01:20:57,880
Food. For the soldiers at the front. Everyone must give their share.

737
01:21:21,480 --> 01:21:23,510
They are taking everything.

738
01:21:24,880 --> 01:21:26,850
Where are the horses?

739
01:21:27,950 --> 01:21:29,790
What horses?

740
01:21:41,370 --> 01:21:44,670
What is it? Leave it if you don't know what it's for.

741
01:21:44,900 --> 01:21:47,740
A pot is a pot. We'll find some use for it.

742
01:21:48,710 --> 01:21:49,730
Sir.

743
01:21:50,640 --> 01:21:54,480
Where's the livestock? l make jam. We have no animals.

744
01:21:54,650 --> 01:21:56,810
But there's fresh hay in your barn.

745
01:21:56,980 --> 01:22:00,610
We use it to replace the mattress stuffings.

746
01:22:06,260 --> 01:22:08,420
Her grandfather? Yes.

747
01:22:08,660 --> 01:22:10,960
Where are her parents? They're dead.

748
01:22:12,330 --> 01:22:13,630
They died.

749
01:22:16,000 --> 01:22:17,030
What is that?

750
01:22:17,340 --> 01:22:20,770
The wind. lt plays tricks in the attic.

751
01:22:21,540 --> 01:22:23,300
There is no wind.

752
01:22:23,610 --> 01:22:25,770
An old house creaks.

753
01:22:25,950 --> 01:22:28,310
Go, close the shutters.

754
01:22:35,490 --> 01:22:37,320
She's sickly, no?

755
01:22:37,560 --> 01:22:42,320
lf you or any of your friends harm her,

756
01:22:43,500 --> 01:22:46,860
as old as l am, l will kill you.

757
01:22:55,980 --> 01:22:57,000
You know,

758
01:22:57,710 --> 01:22:59,870
 l was going to give you back your pot.

759
01:23:00,050 --> 01:23:02,010
But now l'm going to keep it.

760
01:23:04,650 --> 01:23:05,950
For soup.

761
01:23:07,920 --> 01:23:09,680
We will be back.

762
01:23:10,320 --> 01:23:11,880
ln the new season.

763
01:23:36,950 --> 01:23:38,970
Tell me what happened to them.

764
01:23:40,750 --> 01:23:42,780
To my mother and father.

765
01:23:44,620 --> 01:23:47,060
You said you would tell me how they died

766
01:23:48,490 --> 01:23:50,050
on my birthday.

767
01:23:50,430 --> 01:23:52,920
And tomorrow's my birthday.

768
01:23:54,700 --> 01:23:56,460
They died fighting.

769
01:23:58,700 --> 01:23:59,930
Didn't they?

770
01:24:00,870 --> 01:24:02,700
But when the soldiers come,

771
01:24:03,780 --> 01:24:06,070
you do nothing.

