01:57:21,870 --> 01:57:23,900
Look at that horse!

1038
01:57:24,370 --> 01:57:27,610
Look at the muscles he's got. Them long legs.

1039
01:57:27,850 --> 01:57:31,610
They're made for running, horses. Running away from danger.

1040
01:57:33,120 --> 01:57:34,810
Running away is all they have.

1041
01:57:35,250 --> 01:57:37,280
And yet we taught 'em opposite.

1042
01:57:37,590 --> 01:57:39,350
Running into the fray.

1043
01:57:40,790 --> 01:57:42,550
A war horse. Yeah.

1044
01:57:44,390 --> 01:57:45,690
War horse.

1045
01:57:46,400 --> 01:57:47,830
There he is.

1046
01:57:48,230 --> 01:57:50,670
What a strange beast you've become.

1047
01:57:52,870 --> 01:57:54,170
And now?

1048
01:57:54,400 --> 01:57:56,300
l'll take him back with me, yeah?

1049
01:57:56,810 --> 01:58:00,830
Since l supplied the cutters, the horse is mine. This is fair, no?

1050
01:58:01,210 --> 01:58:03,440
ln a pig's eye. He's English, plain to see.

1051
01:58:03,610 --> 01:58:06,380
You mean because he's so filthy? Because he's so smart!

1052
01:58:06,580 --> 01:58:08,610
And you're none too clean yourself.

1053
01:58:11,460 --> 01:58:14,620
We could box. And the winner gets the horse.

1054
01:58:17,160 --> 01:58:18,590
No, thanks, pet.

1055
01:58:18,760 --> 01:58:21,200
 Must be careful not to start a war.

1056
01:58:23,430 --> 01:58:25,400
Do you have a coin of any sort?

1057
01:58:26,500 --> 01:58:28,270
Coin toss? Yeah.

1058
01:58:31,780 --> 01:58:34,680
All right, Fritz, you're on. My name is not Fritz.

1059
01:58:35,180 --> 01:58:36,480
lt is Peter.

1060
01:58:37,710 --> 01:58:39,480
Peter. l'm Colin.

1061
01:58:39,720 --> 01:58:41,810
You call it, Colin. Heads.

1062
01:58:47,520 --> 01:58:51,820
That's the face of my Kaiser, and he does not look pleased with me.

1063
01:58:53,660 --> 01:58:55,430
The horse is yours.

1064
01:58:56,330 --> 01:58:57,890
Gone quiet, hasn't it?

1065
01:58:58,600 --> 01:58:59,760
Yes.

1066
01:59:00,200 --> 01:59:02,640
But wait half an hour and we'll be shooting again.

1067
01:59:02,870 --> 01:59:06,830
l'm a terrible shot, Pete. Don't believe l'll ever hit a target.

1068
01:59:08,480 --> 01:59:09,500
Thanks.

1069
01:59:11,680 --> 01:59:12,910
Cheerio, mate.

1070
01:59:13,280 --> 01:59:15,440
You'll take good care of him, yes? l will.

1071
01:59:15,620 --> 01:59:17,250
Our strange beast.

1072
01:59:17,550 --> 01:59:19,850
And you take care of your own strange self.

1073
01:59:20,490 --> 01:59:21,510
Colin!

1074
01:59:23,230 --> 01:59:27,560
A pair of German cutters. ln memory of your handsome friend from Dusseldorf.

1075
01:59:27,560 --> 01:59:30,930
Thanks. l'll use them back in the garden in South Shields.

1076
01:59:31,370 --> 01:59:33,600
You keep your head down now, Pete, my lad.

1077
01:59:35,710 --> 01:59:38,730
Remarkable. A remarkable horse!

1078
02:00:16,480 --> 02:00:18,310
We're full up. Move on.

1079
02:00:19,950 --> 02:00:21,710
We're full up. Move on.

1080
02:00:24,620 --> 02:00:27,920
The gas got him. We had to wait till morning.

1081
02:00:32,500 --> 02:00:35,330
This can't be all of us. This is all.

1082
02:00:35,530 --> 02:00:37,360
All walking wounded

1083
02:00:37,630 --> 02:00:40,660
away to the dressing station!

1084
02:00:40,900 --> 02:00:44,070
Away to the dressing station!

1085
02:00:58,320 --> 02:00:59,620
Just hold still.

1086
02:00:59,720 --> 02:01:01,490
You're doing so well.

1087
02:01:21,880 --> 02:01:23,970
What's this doing here? We need a vet, sir.

1088
02:01:24,350 --> 02:01:26,710
There are no vets. There are scarcely any horses left.

1089
02:01:26,850 --> 02:01:29,680
He's cut all over, but this leg here has got the worst of it.

1090
02:01:36,660 --> 02:01:38,690
lt's probably tetanus. lt's no good. 

1091
02:01:38,760 --> 02:01:39,790
Please, sir!

1092
02:01:39,830 --> 02:01:42,390
l've all these men to take care of, Corporal. You can see that, can't you?

1093
02:01:42,500 --> 02:01:44,800
Please, sir, this horse can pull through anything!

1094
02:01:56,380 --> 02:01:57,610
What is it?

1095
02:01:58,450 --> 02:02:02,010
lt's a horse they found wandering about in no man's land. Down you go.

1096
02:02:02,390 --> 02:02:06,060
What kind of a horse? Bloody miraculous kind of a horse be my guess.

1097
02:02:06,060 --> 02:02:08,620
Nothing makes it out of no man's land.

1098
02:02:13,660 --> 02:02:15,560
Miraculous horse.

1099
02:02:17,670 --> 02:02:20,100
He was alive, you see, sir, where nothing survives.

1100
02:02:20,470 --> 02:02:24,740
So to me and my mates, to the men, sir, he's... Well, we have high hopes for him.

1101
02:02:24,740 --> 02:02:26,640
You should shoot him now.

1102
02:02:27,610 --> 02:02:30,580
Oh, but l can't. lt'd be a mercy, lad.

1103
02:02:30,810 --> 02:02:32,710
That leg's not going to mend.

1104
02:02:33,080 --> 02:02:34,450
Sergeant.

1105
02:02:35,950 --> 02:02:37,850
Put him out of his misery.

1106
02:02:43,760 --> 02:02:45,730
He's not going to shoot it here, is he?

1107
02:02:45,900 --> 02:02:48,920
What's going on here? They're going to shoot the horse.

1108
02:02:49,170 --> 02:02:51,070
Ladies, if you please.

1109
02:02:51,440 --> 02:02:52,660
Come, nurses.

1110
02:02:57,570 --> 02:03:01,010
All right, back off! Back off!

1111
02:04:12,920 --> 02:04:14,680
Go on, do it again.

1112
02:04:14,850 --> 02:04:15,880
Go on.

1113
02:04:22,930 --> 02:04:24,090
Joey?

1114
02:04:43,080 --> 02:04:44,310
Hello, Joey.

1115
02:04:45,020 --> 02:04:46,780
 Where you been then, eh?

1116
02:04:47,950 --> 02:04:49,780
Where in the world you been?

1117
02:04:50,090 --> 02:04:51,710
Do you know this man?

1118
02:04:52,620 --> 02:04:54,780
What's your name? Narracott.

1119
02:04:54,960 --> 02:04:56,260
Private Albert Narracott, sir.

1120
02:04:56,560 --> 02:04:59,650
lt's just a random horse, Narracott, and too badly injured.

1121
02:04:59,830 --> 02:05:01,730
ls this man in your care? Yes, sir.

1122
02:05:01,830 --> 02:05:06,860
He's not random at all, sir! He's my horse. l raised him, in Devon.

1123
02:05:07,700 --> 02:05:09,260
Sir, look at his legs.

1124
02:05:09,640 --> 02:05:12,130
He's got four white socks, he's brown all over,

1125
02:05:12,280 --> 02:05:14,770
and he has a white mark here, like so.

1126
02:05:18,720 --> 02:05:20,740
Take him back. Come on, son.

1127
02:05:20,920 --> 02:05:23,220
Wait! You can't see 'cause of the mud!

1128
02:05:57,020 --> 02:05:58,250
Four white socks.

1129
02:06:54,880 --> 02:06:58,370
All right, break it up! Clear off, the lot of ya!

1130
02:06:58,880 --> 02:07:00,180
You see, sir? 

1131
02:07:00,750 --> 02:07:02,380
He's not random at all.

1132
02:07:05,160 --> 02:07:06,990
We'll attend to your horse.

1133
02:07:07,760 --> 02:07:09,450
Patch him up best we can.

1134
02:07:10,160 --> 02:07:12,130
Treat him like the soldier he is.

1135
02:07:13,230 --> 02:07:14,720
Thank you, sir.

1136
02:07:40,990 --> 02:07:42,290
Gentlemen!

1137
02:07:43,130 --> 02:07:44,420
Gentlemen!

1138
02:07:44,730 --> 02:07:47,750
lt falls on me to give you some important news.

1139
02:07:47,930 --> 02:07:51,490
At 1 1 :00 today, in two minutes' time,

1140
02:07:51,970 --> 02:07:54,270
the war will come to an end.

1141
02:07:55,810 --> 02:07:58,500
The King and Queen thank you for your service.

1142
02:07:58,940 --> 02:08:00,970
We have been victorious,

1143
02:08:01,140 --> 02:08:04,770
even if it's a higher price than many of us might have imagined.

1144
02:08:04,950 --> 02:08:06,780
When the bells ring out,

1145
02:08:06,950 --> 02:08:10,110
and they will in a moment, for the first time in four years,

1146
02:08:10,290 --> 02:08:13,380
let us remember our brothers fallen in the field,

1147
02:08:13,790 --> 02:08:15,950
and thank God for the end of this struggle,

1148
02:08:17,030 --> 02:08:18,320
and victory.

1149
02:08:33,010 --> 02:08:34,440
l don't understand, sir.

1150
02:08:36,210 --> 02:08:40,580
Officers' horses only. All other horses are to be auctioned immediately.

1151
02:08:40,980 --> 02:08:45,280
That is a complete and bloody outrage. lt's the lad's horse, sir! From Devon.

1152
02:08:45,460 --> 02:08:50,050
He raised him up from a pup, he did. Trained him right up to the day when the army came to town!

1153
02:08:50,130 --> 02:08:52,890
These aren't my orders, Sergeant.

1154
02:08:54,330 --> 02:08:56,490
You'll have to take him to market tomorrow.

1155
02:08:57,800 --> 02:08:58,960
That's all.

1156
02:09:23,830 --> 02:09:25,800
We've all clubbed together.

1157
02:09:26,030 --> 02:09:27,930
lt's everything we have.

1158
02:09:28,970 --> 02:09:32,460
There's 29 pounds there. Buy him back.

1159
02:09:37,540 --> 02:09:38,840
Does the Major know?

1160
02:09:39,010 --> 02:09:41,770
The Major put in 1 0. Mum's the word where the Major's concerned.

1161
02:09:41,950 --> 02:09:43,970
Your friend, on the crutches over there,

1162
02:09:44,150 --> 02:09:47,120
even asked the Major to say that Joey was his, an officer's horse,

1163
02:09:47,580 --> 02:09:49,610
so that he could go back with the others.

1164
02:09:51,090 --> 02:09:54,650
Come on, Narracott, get a move on. We don't want to miss the show.

1165
02:10:04,170 --> 02:10:06,930
Seven pounds! Seven pounds there!

1166
02:10:07,200 --> 02:10:08,230
Seven pounds! 

1167
02:10:08,670 --> 02:10:10,970
Eight pounds here! Eight pounds!

1168
02:10:11,210 --> 02:10:14,230
Ten pounds here! Any advance? Sold!

1169
02:10:14,680 --> 02:10:19,680
All right. No one's going to bid more than 1 5 for a thoroughbred. They want workhorses.

1170
02:10:22,750 --> 02:10:24,190
Next one!

1171
02:10:25,820 --> 02:10:27,650
We start at four pounds!

1172
02:10:28,220 --> 02:10:29,990
Four pounds!

1173
02:10:30,560 --> 02:10:32,720
Five pounds! Five pounds here!

1174
02:10:33,000 --> 02:10:34,960
Any advance? Seven pounds!

1175
02:10:35,270 --> 02:10:37,630
Eight pounds! Nine pounds!

1176
02:10:38,030 --> 02:10:39,590
Ten pounds!

1177
02:10:40,100 --> 02:10:41,130
Eleven pounds!

1178
02:10:41,770 --> 02:10:47,740
lt's the butcher from Cambrai. He's been bidding for the best all morning. Eleven pounds.

1179
02:10:47,740 --> 02:10:50,650
Let me handle this, Private. Fifteen!

1180
02:10:50,850 --> 02:10:52,610
And let that be an end to it!

1181
02:10:52,880 --> 02:10:54,040
Fifteen pounds!

1182
02:10:54,520 --> 02:10:55,810
Sixteen pounds.

1183
02:10:57,050 --> 02:10:58,540
Seventeen!

1184
02:10:58,790 --> 02:11:03,090
Twenty of your English pounds. And let that be the end of it, my friend.

1185
02:11:03,290 --> 02:11:04,780
Twenty pounds!

1186
02:11:05,660 --> 02:11:07,100
Twentyfive pounds!

1187
02:11:07,930 --> 02:11:09,560
Twentysix.

1188
02:11:09,730 --> 02:11:11,030
Twentysix pounds!

1189
02:11:11,130 --> 02:11:13,230
Twentyseven! Twentyeight!

1190
02:11:13,600 --> 02:11:14,830
Twentyeight pounds.

1191
02:11:14,940 --> 02:11:16,060
Twentynine!

1192
02:11:16,240 --> 02:11:17,330
And thirty!

1193
02:11:17,710 --> 02:11:19,680
Any advance on thirty pounds?

1194
02:11:20,010 --> 02:11:22,030
One hundred pounds!

1195
02:11:27,220 --> 02:11:29,650
And, sir, if you bid against me,

1196
02:11:29,820 --> 02:11:34,190
l will sell the coat on my back and bid to 1 1 0.

1197
02:11:34,560 --> 02:11:37,650
And if you bid against me again, l will sell my farm,

1198
02:11:37,830 --> 02:11:39,920
and bid to a thousand!

1199
02:11:43,030 --> 02:11:45,060
One hundred pounds!

1200
02:11:46,640 --> 02:11:48,190
Going, going,

1201
02:11:48,840 --> 02:11:49,860
gone!

1202
02:11:59,250 --> 02:12:00,270
Sir,

1203
02:12:00,650 --> 02:12:04,020
l'll give you all your money, everything you paid,when we get back to England. 

1204
02:12:04,190 --> 02:12:06,680
l'll give you twice what... You don't know anything about him.

1205
02:12:06,860 --> 02:12:08,820
But you're wrong, sir. l know everything.

1206
02:12:08,990 --> 02:12:13,330
Yes, you found him. l heard you found a horse in the wire between the armies.

1207
02:12:13,330 --> 02:12:15,630
No, l found him. He raised him.

1208
02:12:17,730 --> 02:12:21,030
When l heard about the miracle horse, l traveled three days

1209
02:12:21,200 --> 02:12:24,170
because l knew whose horse he was.

1210
02:12:25,010 --> 02:12:26,910
My granddaughter's.

1211
02:12:27,210 --> 02:12:31,040
She saved his life. He was everything to her.

1212
02:12:31,150 --> 02:12:32,910
Where is your granddaughter?

1213
02:12:33,080 --> 02:12:35,850
The war has taken everything from everyone.

1214
02:12:36,020 --> 02:12:38,320
He is all that l have left of her.

1215
02:13:01,840 --> 02:13:03,940
Don't be worried, boy, when l go.

1216
02:13:04,180 --> 02:13:06,270
l won't worry over you none.

1217
02:13:06,820 --> 02:13:08,780
Hey, l found you, didn't l?

1218
02:13:10,120 --> 02:13:11,880
And you found me.

1219
02:13:15,860 --> 02:13:17,290
And we'll both...

1220
02:13:18,190 --> 02:13:20,360
We'll both know that we made it through.

1221
02:13:21,200 --> 02:13:22,690
Now come on.

1222
02:13:23,730 --> 02:13:26,430
We're the lucky ones. Always have been.

1223
02:13:26,870 --> 02:13:28,890
Lucky since the day l met you.

1224
02:13:31,710 --> 02:13:33,140
God be with you, sir.

1225
02:13:36,150 --> 02:13:38,050
Do you know what this is?

1226
02:13:42,350 --> 02:13:44,110
That's my father's.

1227
02:13:44,820 --> 02:13:46,850
That's his regimental pennant.

1228
02:13:53,760 --> 02:13:55,790
How did you come by this, sir?

1229
02:13:58,100 --> 02:13:59,860
You may have this.

1230
02:14:08,440 --> 02:14:11,070
Thank you ever so much for this, sir.

1231
02:14:14,920 --> 02:14:16,280
And this.

1232
02:14:25,360 --> 02:14:26,790
Sir, l... No, no, no.

1233
02:14:26,960 --> 02:14:29,860
Not necessary. He belongs to you.

1234
02:14:30,730 --> 02:14:33,760
That is, of course, what my little girl would have wanted.

1235
02:14:34,000 --> 02:14:35,970
And she was the boss.

1236
02:14:47,050 --> 02:14:48,350
What was her name?

1237
02:14:49,220 --> 02:14:50,520
Emilie.

1238
02:14:54,020 --> 02:14:56,050
Her name is Emilie.

1239
02:17:58,710 --> 02:18:02,240

